column5: Approved for lessons by I Can Swim
column14: Per parent report, Stetson will going swimming at his grandmothers house. When swimming at his grandmother's house he will sit or stand on a landing step and walk around, splash and play. An adult will pick him up and hold him to take him out to swim. Stetson will go up to his neck in water. Stetson loves Daniel Tiger, rubber ducks and playing with pool noodles. When communicating, Stetson is able to verbally imitate and will perform the sign for "swim" with support from the instructor.
column15: During the assessment, Stetson refused to enter the water. He was telling his father that he wanted to go back to the truck and go home. The new environment and new instructor could have contributed to Stetson's hesitation with getting in the water. He was also taken to the pool at 9:00am and Dad mentioned that this interfered with his morning routine.  During a conversation the Mr. Grover, he mentioned that when Stetson is in the pool he does not like to get his face or head wet. His goals would be for Stetson to learn how to swim independently and to learn survival skills. He mentioned that Stetson is fearless and does not understand the dangers around water. Mom mentioned that there was a scary incident in the past that occurred in water with one of Stetson's siblings and this has created some anxieties for the family around water. Stetson oftentimes jumps off of items and parents have a fear that he will jump into a pool. With this information, the instructor decided to approve Stetson for swim lessons to help him become more comfortable in the water and to learn the essential swim skill necessary for safety. The instructor also mentioned to mom that we will begin lessons with a life vest on to ensure everyone is comfortable and that Stetson is safe during his lessons. With time, we will fade the life jacket and teach Stetston the swim skills with the life jacket removed.

column5: Approved for lessons by I Can Swim
column14: Adonis' mother reports that they have a pool at their apartment complex in which Adonis enjoys swimming in. Adonis is always in a life vest when swimming. Mom mentioned that they put his life vest on at the apartment and will walk down to the pool. They do not leave the house without it. He is very comfortable in the water- almost too comfortable in her opinion which causes fear. Mom mentions that Adonis enjoys going under water and doing front flips. He also enjoys being thrown in the air by his father. Mom reports that Adonis has many emerging swim skills; however, they are all performed in his life vest. He will use a combination of gestures and verbalizations to ask permission to enter the pool.
column15: On the day of the assessment, Adonis refused to enter the water. He would tell his mother, " I want to go home". Adonis was very nervous to get in. The assessment was cut short due to Adonis' refusal to enter the water; however, his mother, Mayra and the instructor held a phone conversation in which mom reports that when submerging, Adonis will stay under water for too long and will accidentally consume water. He has never jumped in on his own; however, he has gotten very close to the water on two occasions. Mayra described herself as not being the strongest swimmer so when Adonis gets too close to water this makes her fear that she won't be able to help or that they would both be in danger especially since she also has another son who is a toddler. She would just like for Adonis to learn how to be safe around water and to gain some survival and independent swim skills. When Adonis returned home after the assessment, he told his mother, "The pool is too big for me". Mayra informed the instructor and together decided that during his first lesson that Adonis would begin with his life vest on to see if that will make him feel a little more comfortable.

column14: Mom reports that Alasdair enjoys playing in water. They have an inflatable pool at home that he enjoys playing in. When swimming in bigger bodies of water he will wear a life vest and will not try to remove it. Alaisdair has also worn a puddle jumper. He will tolerate his face getting wet briefly. Mom mentioned that he loves receiving positive praise. Alasdair communicates uses PECS, gestures, hand leading and is learning how to use an AAC. During the assessment, Alasdair was able to hold onto equipment, attempt to back float with his head above water and tolerated support provided by the instructor.
column15: Mom mentioned that the safety aspect of being around water is the most important for her. Alasdair has recently jumped into water while visiting the Great Wolf Lodge and his mother had to jump in after him to get him. He had a lifevest on but was unable to stand up or bring his head out of the water. When having a difficult time, Alasdair responds well to counting and offering hugs. During the assessment, Alasdiar was observed to hold on tightly to the instructor. He preferred for her to be in close proximity to him when jumping into the pool and he preferred to hold onto her while swimming. He did not put his face in the water during the assessment but he did tolerate the instructor pouring water over his head. Alasdair's body was very tense throughout the assessment, so it was challenging for the instructor to help move his arms and legs at times.

column14: Parent reports that Miko previously has taken a couple swim lessons. Last summer his grandparents bought an above ground pool and Miko spent much of his time swimming in which he has learned basic swim skills. Miko is able to wear goggles while swimming. He is able to submerge to retrieve items and he is able to frontcrawl.
column15: Per mom, Miko is fearless and has no safety awareness around water. He is confident in water but this worries his mother because at times he can become overly confident and miscalculate the dangers that may arise. Mom would like for Miko to learn how to be safe around water, improve his swimming skills and develop better swimming technique. During the assessment, Miko would frequently submerge under water. The instructor would cue him to swim "on top" of the water but Miko still needed occasional prompts to refrain from submerging. Miko was also observed to no be as confident on his back. Mom mentioned that he has Moro reflex which makes going on his back a little more difficult. When the instructor would provide equipment to hold, Miko was observed to push it under his body, let go of it or try to submerge with it. He is not yet holding onto the equipment appropriately. When instructed to walk in water, Miko would bounce on the bottom of the pool and then glide. He was not yet alternating his feet while on they were place on the floor, independently.

column5: Approved for lessons by I Can Swim
column14: Parents report that Levi enjoys swimming. When the family goes to the pool, Levi will typically stay on the stairs to splash and play. He always wears a life jacket when going in the pool. He does not attempt to take it off. Levi has never taken swim lessons prior. Mom reports that he will lay on the steps and tilt his head back, occassionally. Levi's best mode for communicating is is PECS. He will also make sounds to let you know he does not like something. During the assessment, Levi allowed the instructor to hold him to take him into the pool. The instructor and Levi walked up and down in the shallow end. Levi had a very strong grip on the instructor and he did not like when she would try to release her hold. Levi was also able to blow bubbles while in the water.
column15: Mom mentions that when in the pool with his life jacket, Levi will refuse to let her hold him. Parents mention that Levi will elope at times and he is extremely drawn to water which makes them fearful that he will jump into the water and not be able to keep himself safe. Recently, while visiting Great Wolf Lodge, Levi jumped into the water on his own and an adult had to retrieve him. Upon arrival to the assessment, Levi was eager to get in the water. His mother and father had to physically prompt him to wait and not enter the water. Once the instructor was ready and told Levi to enter the pool, he refused and dropped to the floor.  Levi's father had to assist the instructor to get Levi into the pool. During the assessment, Levi was extremely uncomfortable while in the water without his life jacket on. He held onto the instructor very tight in which it she had to ask for help from another instructor to loosen his grasp. Levi was also observed to open his mouth in the pool in which he would occasionally consume water.  The instructor mentioned that if approved, during his first few lessons parents will bring his lifejacket from home to ensure he can be a little more comfortable.

column5: Approved for lessons by I Can Swim
column14: Willow shared that she wants to learn how to swim without a lifejacket but that she is nervous in the water. Willow was excited to be at swim school but told instructor she was nervous. Instructor started with walking in the shallow end holding onto the side. From there Willow practiced walking in the shallow end away from the walk. She was a little unbalanced and instructor placed weights on her feet and Will said that the weights really helped. She then was able to walk in the shallow end by herself. She was nervous to lift her feet in the water. So instructor had her work on foot work in the water (i.e. lifting legs, side steps, jumps and backwards walks). She began to feel more comfortable. From there was she able to go under water and hold her breath for a few seconds holding onto the side. She was able to be shown how to climb out in the shallow and seal slide into the water. Willow likes to be shown what is being asked of her and giving her a safe space to try it on her own.
column15: Parent shared that when she goes into the water with a lifejacket, she stays close to the steps. Willow should continue to work on her body awareness in water. Learning how water works and how she can float on her own. She likes to be shown what to do then given the space to try it on her own.

column14: Dad mentioned that Izen usually takes a few minutes to warm up while in the water. He reports that when they swim together he is able to hold him and allow him to splash, play and occasionally submerge him under water. When this happened, Izen began putting his tongue in the water and attempting to drink the water.  When in close proximity to the stairs, Izen attempted to elope from the pool. This also occurred when the instructor had him climb out of the pool.

column5: Approved for lessons by I Can Swim
column14: Per mom, Adrian typically wears a puddle jumper when swimming; however, they used to have an above ground pool in their backyard and Adrian did not like to wear his puddlejumper because he would stand in the water. Mom reports that he is very confident in their shallow, above ground pool but she would like for him to become a stronger independent swimmer. During the assessment, Adrian was observed to have great foundational skills for swimming. He was able to submerge his face under water, walk in the water, front float, roll over, jump into the pool and front/back crawl. Adrian was able to independently climb out of the pool, jump in and return to the side of the pool as well as move laterally while holding onto the side of the pool. He listened and participated to all instructions provided especially when given a model and front loaded with expectations.
column15: Mom reports that Adrian has an older brother that he often swims with and she would like for Adrian to be able to be safe while swimming with him. She would like for him to improve his swim strokes and potentially learn how to swim in a current because the family visits the lakes in rivers occasionally. During the assessment, Adrian held his breath frequently. He required support to submerge to depths greater than 3 feet, and is swimming with his head above water.

column15: Jeremy is very nervous in the water. Moving forward, instructor should start with a tight hold and then loosen and change holds to build in comfort.

column5: Approved for lessons by I Can Swim
column14: Mia was very excited to get in the water. She is able to sign that she wants to swim. Her sign is a hands rolling motion. Parent shared that they have been working on her swim skills this summer. That Mia has preferred to stay in a life jacket. Instructor heard concerns regarding her being a little scared in water at times and decided to started the lessons with body awareness in the water and teaching Mia want she should be doing to keep her safe. Instructor showed Mia that she needs to be standing in the shallow and walking or hopping to the stairs. To hold onto the side to get breath and pop herself up if she goes under. She also wore ankle weights to give her a little more control in the shallow end. From there, Mia went under water. She was able to go under for 5-7 seconds. When she comes up she tends to suck water in through her nose. She needs cueing to remember to blow out. Instructor then built a swim skills lesson, each time allowing her to add a skill. Float, kicks, submersion.
column15: Mia should continue to skill build through the lesson. She did well reviewing on isolated skill then adding the next. She needs help motor planning her front crawl and breathing out air when she comes up.

column14: Axcel's mom reports that they have access to a pool at family members' home. When they go swimming he typically wears a life jacket and will doggy paddle around the pool while in his life jacket. Mom mentioned that Axcel enjoys being in the water. During the assessment, Axcel listened to instructor and was open to trying new activities. He did want to try skills on his own and was observed to say, "I can do it myself"; however, he does require support from the instructor to prevent him from going under water. Axcel wore regular goggles that he brought from home. With prompting from the instructor, Axcel was able to verbally ask permission to enter the pool.
column15: Axcel is eager to swim independently; however, he is not quite yet ready to do so without support from the instructor or equipment. Mom reports that Axcel does not like water in his eyes. She also mentioned that Axcel will run around the pool. On at least one occasion, he slipped and fell while running. In the past, Axcel has been fearful of the water; however, within the last year or so he has become more comfortable and excited to be in the water. During the assessment, Axcel had attempted to elope from the pool to retrieve items. Mom also had to remind him not to approach the pool until it was time to get in. Mom reports that he is curious about the water and that safety is a priority. When Axcel is upset, Mom says that taking deep breaths and counting to 3 are helpful for him.

column14: Aubrey was able to walk into the water with guidance. Parent shared that she likes to stand in the shallow end but will go out in deeper water with lifejacket on. Aubrey was able to stand in the shallow end. She did not like touch from instructor. However, when she had a lifejacket on she would hold onto instructor. This seems to be a better strategy for Aubrey. Letting her ask/need physical support. An AAC was shown at assessment. She was able to imitate and choose the next swim activity. She went into a lifejacket and wants to keep her feet pointed down. Instructor gave warming prior to lifting her legs. (i.e. 1,2,3, lift) then would use leg to help lift her legs up to support her then would count 1-5 down. After two floats back and forth lifting legs, would get a break in the shallow end with no demand. Giving Aubrey a chance to relax before swimming again.
column15: Aubrey did well with routines and first/then. Counting and cueing helped Aubrey transition.  Aubrey also did well with hands on breaks before given another tasks. She is a little nervous with float feeling or feet leaving the ground.

column14: Arianna's mother reports that the family has a pool at home and she loves being in the water. Mom says that Arianna's receptive communication is stronger than her expressive communication. When the instructor asked Arianna to submerge to retrieve an item off the stairs, Arianna would keep her face out of the water. Arianna also needs support to coordinate her arm and leg patterns to efficient swim independently.

column14: Parent shared that Blayne LOVES the water but is very concerned about his overall safety around water. He will dart and take off. Parent has to keep hands on and very close when around water. When Blayne got into the water he was consistently going under water. He would drop to the bottom of the pool and wait for a cue to come up. He would throw his head back and get water in his nose. He was not waiting to get a full breath before going back under. Different strategies were tried: visual for choice, visuals for schedule, first/then, my turn your turn, verbal praise, breaks out of the pool. column15: Based on water safety concerns and behavior seen we can implement: Creating a multi step water entry routine. Would like to create swim routines for Blayne to learn new swim skills. Letting him earn under waters.

column14: Colt has taken swim lessons in the water but is not yet swimming on his own. Parent shared that her main concern is his impulsivity around water and wants to make he is safe. Colt was able to ask to get in the water and was walked to the stairs. He was able to stand on the steps and play with toys. Colt was ok with different types of physical holds from instruction. He did not like to be on his back with ears in the water. Instructor started out with lay back position full hug and slowly got ears in for a short amount of time. He was able to go under water but tends to suck water in when he comes up. He was able to breath out when give cues. By the end of the assessment, he did much better blowing air out when he came up. He was able to climb out from the side with a few teaching opportunities. Colt loves to jump in. He jumped without caution or seeing if adult would help. He was able to hold onto the side of the pool and hand walk. He did let go of the side and need a physical prompt to reach back for the side.
column15: Colt should work on putting safety routines in place around hand walking (holding the side), climbing out of the pool, asking to get in, jumping in and swimming back to side. He should work on front crawl swims and getting more relaxed with his back float.

column5: Approved for lessons by I Can Swim
column14: Max was excited to get in the water. He was able to walk with instructor to the stairs. He was able to repeat "swim please" to ask mom. Once in the water, Max wanted to go under. Instructor gave Max time to bounce and go under water in the shallow end. Once he was able to get his wiggles out instructor tried different ways to support him. He was not tolerating touch and would push hand away. However, he was showing interested in sinky toys. Since he likes to go under, instructor then used the sinky toys to motivate swimming and tolerate touch. He was then able to tolerate touch for support to go and get sinky toys. Instructor kept building on the swim under routine. Max was then able to go into a supported back float roll into a swim to go under and grab toys. He likes the dory sinky toy (blue fish). Then instructor used the toys to motivate for non-preferred tasks such as wearing waistbelt, kicking feet on noodle, using barbell etc. Parent shared that new activities can be challenging for Max.
column15: I would recommend using under games to support different holds. Use the toy as motivation for non-preferred. Pick a few new drills each lesson and then build. Use first then strategy. Give time to allow him to jump and go under at the beginning of the lesson and during for breaks. Max's whole body mellowed at the end. Needs transition warning at the end of swim.

column5: Approved for lessons by I Can Swim
column14: Initially Tadeo was very uncomfortable in the water; however, over time he became more and more relaxed. Tadeo allowed the instructor to hold him and he also tolerated wearing equipment (I.e backpack float). Tadeo's mother mentioned that he can imitate one word statements but his best form of communicating that was observed was gestures. Tadeo hears primarily Spanish throughout his day. The instructor attempted to provide instructions in Spanish and English when possible as well as providing model prompts. To communicate his wants, Tadeo would oftentimes tap the instructor's shoulder and point to a desired item. Tadeo showed signs of enjoyment by smiling while playing with the toys, especially the watering can. When the instructor would provide support around Tadeo's waist he would perform a sculling motion with his hands but moving his hands and arms in and out. His mother says that he will tolerate wearing a backpack but that he has never been in a large body of water before.
column15: When initially entering the water, Tadeo needed encouragement from his mother and then instructor to enter the water. He was observed to attempt to exit the pool within the first couple of minutes of beginning the assessment. Over time, Tadeo became more comfortable. Once in the water, Tadeo did not attempt to elope again. While swimming, Tadeo was observed to inhale when his mouth would go under water. When this would occur he would cough. The instructor began teaching him close mouth when under then breath. Tadeo was beginning to imitate these motions. While swimming, Tadeo is very stiff. His legs do not move often and when the instructor tried to physically prompt him his legs were very tense. Tadeo also does not like water on his face. His mother reports that Tadeo is curious around water but does not have any safety awareness. She has to be in close proximity to him to ensure that he does not enter water. She mentions that he can be impulsive at times and she wants him to learn water safety skills and how to become a more independent swimmer.

column5: Approved for lessons by I Can Swim
column14: Lillian also goes by the nickname, "Lilly". She demonstrated many strengths throughout the assessment. She had many foundational swim skills such as front/back float, submerging to retrieve items in shallow water, proper kicking form, bilateral movement with arms during front/back crawl. Lily also preferred wearing full face goggles but hesitantly put on regular goggles and did well while wearing these too. When given equipment, Lily was safely using it and would maintain control of the equipment while using it. Lily had emerging skills within her ability to jump in, streamline and treading water.
column15: During the assessment, Lily was observed to be hesitant or nervous about performing some skills; however, the instructor frontloaded her with information and modeled all skills and this strategy seemed to make Lily more comfortable to try skills on her own. Lily appeared nervous while approaching deep water and while jumping in. She verbalized that she does not like to jump in but despite this fear she was able to hold onto the instructor's hand and jump into the pool. Lily was successful when submerging to retrieve toys in the 3ft area; however, she needed a slight, "boost" from the instructor when trying to retrieve items in depths deeper than 3ft. In regards. to wearing a life vest, Lily's mother reports that she will tolerate wearing one but does not have a lot of experience swimming while wearing a life jacket.

column14: Per parents, Himmat has previously taken a two week "intro to water" course in which he would get in the pool with a parent and the parent would hold him but he has not taken lessons or been in the water in the absence of a parent. He was comfortable at first, as long as parents were close by; however, he became uncomfortable when the instructor was changing her holds and trying to hold him out farther away from her body. At this point, Hiimmat wanted to exit the pool and be "all done".  Building comfortability with the water and the instructors will be utmost importance and well as teaching safety skills.

column14: Per mom, the family has a hot tub at home in which Santino plays in. He typically stands up and plays. He will occasionally wear a life vest or a puddle jumper. He has also been observed to put his face in the water while playing in the hot tub. He typically likes to splash and play with toys while in the water. During the assessment, Santino was  able to blow bubbles and had emerging skills within his ability to front float and swim while holding onto with equipment.
column15: Mom mentioned that Santino enjoys playing in water and will approach water on his own. Her priority is for Santino to learn how to be safe, swim independently and learn survival skills in the water. Mom reports that Santino will open his mouth and swish water. This was also observed during the assessment. The instructor suggested bringing his "chewy" to swim lessons to help reduce the consumption of water. During the assessment, Santino would kick away from the instructor while wearing a floatation device. He preferred swimming on his own. When given equipment to hold (I.e barbell, noodles) he is not yet holding onto them for the duration of the lap. He will let go and attempt to swim on his own. When the instructor was placing equipment on Santino, such as a waist belt, and she needed to sit him on the side of the pool it presented some challenges because Santino refused to sit on the edge. This could potentially be because he may have thought the lesson was ending. The instructor explained to him that they were going to put equipment on then get back in the pool and this helped Santino understand the expectations and he allowed her to place the equipment on him.

column14: Sophia was all smiles getting into the pool. She was able to hold hand of instructor and walk into the pool using the stairs. column14: Parent shared that Alejandro is nervous to get in the water. He brough in a slinky toy to the pool. He was able to stand next to mom while we talked about the program. Parent also shared that when he goes to the lake he will wear a lifejacket ( not his favorite to wear) and sit at the shore. Alejandro was able to walk to the stairs with parent.Once at the stairs, he did not want to get in with instructor. Instructor asked permission to help him get in the water. He then sat on the stairs with instructor for a few minutes to get comfortable. He seemed interested in the toys. Instructor gave him a tight hug/hold on the hip and walked him across the pool in the water to get toys. He pointed to get back to the stairs. We repeated this a few times to build comfort. We were then able to leave the toys out in the water and try to get them. Alejandro started smiling and instructor could feel his body start to relax. He then went into a arms around instructors arms with feet out hold. Instructor asked him if he was "ready to fly?" and then put him in a front float position supported with arms. He started smiling. Parent also shared Alejandro does where glasses at school. He tends to look up at the ceiling if his glasses are not on. He also watches his tablet at a hand up view. This is something to note when modeling or showing him visuals at the pool. He was able to put his mouth in the water. He liked popping instructors bubbles in the water. He needs support to climb out from the side of the pool, but fell into instructors arms off the side ( no under water)
column15: Alejandro should continue to work on water comfort and build trust with his instructor. Use play and games to help. He likes to start with tight holds to bring comfort then start loosening holds to increase independence. Alejandro should work on kicking motions of his feet with equipment if needed, as well as asking to get in water, climbing out, jumping in and submerging.

column5: Approved for lessons by I Can Swim
column14: Per mother, Pablo enjoys being in the water. They do not have a pool at home. During the assessment, Pablo was very hesitant to perform skills with the instructor; however, after spending time building rapport and comfort Pablo was able to blow bubbles, attempt to back float and kick his feet. Pablo was also able to glide into the water with instructor support. Pablo was much more inclined to perform a skill when given a verbal instruction paired with a visual. Pablo is verbal and is able to ask permission to enter the water with a prompt; however, he is very shy and only responded  occasionally with one word during the assessment.
column15: Pablo does not like water in his face and he is not yet fully comfortable in the water. Pablo told the instructor that he does not like to jump or go under water. He is very stiff when swimming. For example, while kicking his feet his legs were fully bent and only kicking with the lower half of his leg. He is not yet floating or able to coordinate movement to keep his head above water.
